    Introduction: Density ratio estimation for covariate shift

    Print a naivedensityratio object

    print.naivedensityratio.Rd

    Print a naivedensityratio object

    Usage

    # S3 method for naivedensityratio
print(x, digits = max(3L, getOption("digits") - 3L), ...)

    Arguments

    x

    Object of class naivesubspacedensityratio.

    digits

    Number of digits to use when printing the output.

    ...

    further arguments on how to format the number of digits.

    Value

    invisble The inputted naivedensityratio object.

    See also

    print, naive

    Examples

    set.seed(123)
# Fit model
dr <- naive(numerator_small, denominator_small)
# Inspect model object
dr
#> 
#> Call:
#> naive(df_numerator = numerator_small, df_denominator = denominator_small)
#> 
#> Naive density ratio
#>   Number of variables: 3
#>   Number of numerator samples: 50
#>   Number of denominator samples: 100
#>   Numerator density: num [1:50] 1.41 5.74 1.87 4.13 1.67 ...
#>   Denominator density: num [1:100] 2.93 0.071 1.065 1.59 2.115 ...
#>  
# Obtain summary of model object
summary(dr)
#> 
#> Call:
#> naive(df_numerator = numerator_small, df_denominator = denominator_small)
#> 
#> Naive density ratio estimate:
#>   Number of variables: 
#>   Number of numerator samples: 50
#>   Number of denominator samples: 100
#>   Density ratio for numerator samples: num [1:50] 1.41 5.74 1.87 4.13 1.67 ...
#>   Density ratio for denominator samples: num [1:100] 2.93 0.071 1.065 1.59 2.115 ...
#>  
#> 
#> Squared average log density ratio difference for numerator and denominator samples (SALDRD): 3.025
#> For a two-sample homogeneity test, use 'summary(x, test = TRUE)'.

plot(dr)
